{"title_page": "Noah (name)", "text_new": "'''Noah''' is a [[given name]] and [[surname]] most likely derived from the [[The Bible|Biblical]] figure [[Noah]] (\u05e0\u05d5\u05b9\u05d7\u05b7) in [[Hebrew]]. It is also the other name for a retarded unicorn owned by santa,It is most likely of Babylonian and Assyrian origin from the word \"nukhu\" meaning repose or rest, which is possible in view of the Sumerian/Babylonian source of the flood story. Another explanation says that it is derived from the Hebrew root meaning \"to comfort\" (nahum) with the final consonant dropped.<ref>Oxford Dictionary of First Names</ref>\n\n==Popularity==\n\nFrom 2013 until 2015, the name was the most popular male name in the US.<ref name=\"Popularity of Noah in the United States\"<ref name=\"Popularity of Noah in the United States\">[http://www.ssa.gov/OACT/babynames/top5names.html Popularity of Noah in the United States]</ref>\nIn 2013 it was the third [[List of most popular given names#Male names 5|most popular name for boys in Australia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://parenting.kidspot.com.au/australias-100-most-popular-baby-names/#.Us8-yqxBRPh|title=Australia\u2019s 100 most popular baby names|publisher=Kidspot|date=April 2, 2013|accessdate=2014-01-10|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110091657/http://parenting.kidspot.com.au/australias-100-most-popular-baby-names/#.Us8-yqxBRPh|archivedate=January 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Variants in other languages==\n* [[Arabic language|Arabic]]: \u0646\u064f\u0648\u062d\u0652 (''N\u016b\u1e25'')\n* [[Armenian language|Armenian]]: \u0546\u0578\u0575 (''Noy'')\n* [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]]: \u041d\u043e\u0439 (''Noy'')\n* [[Catalan language|Catalan]]: No\u00e8\n* [[Czech language|Czech]]: Noe\n* [[Dutch language|Dutch]]: No\u00eb\n* [[Finnish language|Finnish]]: Nooa\n* [[French language|French]]: No\u00e9\n* [[Georgian language|Georgian]]: \u10dc\u10dd\u10d4 (''Noe'')\n* [[Greek language|Greek]]: \u039d\u03ce\u03b5 (''No\u00e9'')\n* [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]]: \u05e0\u05b9\u05d7\u05b7 (''Noakh'')\n* [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]]: No\u00e9\n* [[Italian language|Italian]]: No\u00e8\n* [[Icelandic language|Icelandic]]: N\u00f3i\n* [[Latvian language|Latvian]]: Noass\n* [[Lithuanian language|Lithuanian]]: Nojus\n* [[Polish language|Polish]]: Noe\n* [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]: No\u00e9\n* [[Romanian language|Romanian]]: Noe\n* [[Russian language|Russian]]: \u041d\u043e\u0439 (''Noy'')\n* [[Spanish language|Spanish]]: No\u00e9\n* [[Serbian language|Serbian]]: Noje (''Noye'')\n* [[Turkish language|Turkish]]: Nuh\n* [[Yoruba language|Yoruba]]: Noa\n\n==People with this given name==\n===In modern times===\n* [[Noah Adams]], author, senior correspondent for National Public Radio, and former co-host of ''All Things Considered''\n* [[Noah Baumbach]], American independent film writer-director\n* [[Noah Beauchamp]], blacksmith and Indiana pioneer\n* [[Noah Beery Sr]], American actor\n** [[Noah Beery Jr]], American actor and son of the former\n* [[Noah Boeken]], Dutch professional poker and ''Magic: The Gathering'' player\n* [[Noah Brooks]], American journalist and editor\n* [[Noah Brown (American football)]], American football player\n* [[Noah Buschel]], American writer and director\n* [[Noah Cantor]], Canadian CFL player\n* [[Noah Centineo]], American actor\n* [[Noah Chesmain]], English footballer\n* [[Noah Cyrus]], American singer and former child actress\n* [[Noah Dawkins]] (born 1997), American football player\n* [[Noach Dear]] (1953\u20132020), [[New York Supreme Court]] judge\n* [[Noah Emmerich]], American actor\n* [[Noah Eli Gordon]], American poet\n* [[Noah Fant]] (born 1997), American football player\n* [[Noah Gordon (novelist)|Noah Gordon]], American novelist\n* [[Noah Gordon (singer)|Noah Gordon]], American country music singer\n* [[Noah Gray-Cabey]], American child actor\n* [[Noah Hathaway]], American actor\n* [[Noah Hoffman]], American Olympic skier\n* [[Noah Howard]], American free jazz musician\n* [[Noah Hutchings]], president of Southwest Radio Church Ministries\n* [[Noah Jupe]], English actor\n* [[Noah Kalina]], creator of the film ''Everyday''\n* [[Noah Lennox]], aka Panda Bear, founding member of the band [[Animal Collective]]\n* [[Noah Lewis]], American jug band musician, known for playing the harmonica\n* [[Noah Lukeman]], American author, actor and literary agent\n* [[Noah Mann]], English cricketer\n* [[Noah Miller]], Canadian water polo player\n* [[Noah Mills]], Canadian model and actor\n* [[Noah Mozes]] (1912\u201385), Israeli newspaper publisher and managing editor\n* [[Noah Munck]] (born 1996), American actor\n* [[Noah Ngeny]], Kenyan athlete\n* [[Noah Noble]], Whig governor of the US state of Indiana from 1831 to 1837\n* [[Noah Palmer]], American soccer player\n* [[Noah Porter]], American educationalist and philosophical writer\n* [[Noah Qudah]], Jordanian Grand Mufti\n* [[Noah John Rondeau]], hermit in the Adirondack Mountains\n* [[Noah Robbins]], American actor\n* [[Noah Rubin (tennis)|Noah Rubin]] (born 1996), American tennis player\n* [[Noah Schnapp]], American actor\n* [[Noah Skaalum]] (born 1995), Danish singer, formerly known as Sarah Skaalum\n* [[Noah Song]] (born 1997), American professional baseball player\n* [[Noah Syndergaard]] (born 1992), American professional baseball player\n* [[Noah Haynes Swayne]], American jurist and politician\n* [[Noah Taylor]], London-born Australian actor\n* [[Noah Verhoeven]], Canadian soccer player\n* [[Noah Watts]], Native American Actor and Musician \n* [[Noah Webster]], American lexicographer, textbook author, spelling reformer, political writer, and editor\n* [[Noah Wyle]], American actor\n* [[Noah Young]] (1887\u20131958), American weightlifter turned actor\n\n===Figures in religious texts===\n* [[Noah]], a major figure in the Hebrew Bible\n* Noah, one of the five [[Daughters of Zelophehad]] in the Hebrew Bible\n* [[King Noah]], a wicked Nephite king from the Book of Mormon who burned the prophet Abinadi at the stake\n* [[List of Book of Mormon people#N|Noah]], an early Jaredite king in the Book of Mormon\n\n===Fictional characters===\n* [[Minor characters of the Fullmetal Alchemist anime#Noa|Noah]], a minor character in the anime ''Fullmetal Alchemist''\n* [[Noah]], renamed after being dubbed in Japanese, originally Beyal, a monk and one of the main protagonists of animated television series ''[[Monsuno]]''\n* [[List of Soul Eater characters#Noah|Noah]], a group of artificial beings created from the Book of Eibon in manga ''[[Soul Eater (manga)|Soul Eater]]''\n* Noah in the Canadian television series ''[[Total Drama (series)|Total Drama]]''\n* Noah Beckett in the television show ''[[Second Noah]]''\n* [[Noah Bennet]] in the NBC drama ''Heroes''\n* [[Noah Bennett]] in daytime drama ''Passions''\n* Noah Calhoun in the 2004 film [[The Notebook (2004 film)|''The Notebook'']] \n* Noah Carver in the ''[[Power Rangers Megaforce]]''\n* [[Noah Daniels]] in the American series ''24''\n* [[Noah Drake]] in ABC's daytime drama ''General Hospital''\n* Noah Hicks, an agent in the American series ''[[Alias (TV series)|Alias]]''\n* Noah Jackson in ''[[The Latest Buzz]]''\n* Noah Joad in John Steinbeck's novel ''[[The Grapes of Wrath]]''\n* [[Noah Kaiba]], an antagonist in manga and anime ''Yu-Gi-Oh!''\n* Noah Keller, a major character in the 2002 psychological horror movie ''[[The Ring (2002 film)|The Ring]]''\n* Noah King, a cartoon character in the television show ''[[Noah and Saskia]]''\n* [[Calculator (comics)|Noah Kuttler]], a supervillain in the [[DC Universe]]\n* [[Noah Lawson]] in the Australian soap ''Home and Away''\n* [[Noah Mayer]] in the CBS soap opera ''As the World Turns''\n* [[Noah Newman]] in the CBS soap opera ''The Young and the Restless''\n* Noah Nichols in the Logo TV series ''[[Noah's Arc (TV series)|Noah's Arc]]''\n* [[List of characters in Atomic Betty#Noah Parker|Noah Parker]], a 12-year-old boy in the animated series ''Atomic Betty''\n* [[Puck (Glee)|Noah \"Puck\" Puckerman]], a character in the Fox series ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]''\n* [[Characters of Final Fantasy XII#Gabranth|Noah fon Ronsenburg]], also known as Gabranth, a major character in the video game ''Final Fantasy XII''\n* Noah Sweetwine in Jandy Nelson's ''I'll Give You The Sun''\n* [[Noah Tate]] in the ITV soap ''Emmerdale''\n* [[Noah Taylor (Desperate Housewives)|Noah Taylor]] in the ABC television series ''Desperate Housewives''\n* Noah Tomten, the main character of the [[PBS Kids]] series ''[[Noddy (TV series)|Noddy]]''\n\n==People with this surname==\n* [[Harold J. Noah]], American educationist\n* [[Joakim Noah]], Yannick's son, American-French basketball player\n* [[John Noah]], American ice hockey player\n* [[Mordecai Manuel Noah]], American playwright, diplomat, journalist, and utopian\n* [[Peter Noah]], American television writer and producer\n* [[Tim Noah]], American children's entertainer\n* [[Timothy Noah]], American writer\n* [[Trevor Noah]], South African comedian\n* [[Yannick Noah]], Zacharie's son, French tennis player and popular music performer\n* [[Zacharie Noah]], Cameroonian footballer who played professionally in France\n\n===Fictional characters===\n* Gertrude Noah, a main character on the British sitcom ''[[Come Back Mrs. Noah]]''\n\n==See also==\n* [[Noa (disambiguation)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{given name|type=both}}\n\n[[Category:Hebrew masculine given names]]\n[[Category:English-language unisex given names]]\n", "text_old": "'''Noah''' is a [[given name]] and [[surname]] most likely derived from the [[The Bible|Biblical]] figure [[Noah]] (\u05e0\u05d5\u05b9\u05d7\u05b7) in [[Hebrew]]. It is most likely of Babylonian and Assyrian origin from the word \"nukhu\" meaning repose or rest, which is possible in view of the Sumerian/Babylonian source of the flood story. Another explanation says that it is derived from the Hebrew root meaning \"to comfort\" (nahum) with the final consonant dropped.<ref>Oxford Dictionary of First Names</ref>\n\n==Popularity==\n\nFrom 2013 until 2015, the name was the most popular male name in the US.<ref name=\"Popularity of Noah in the United States\"<ref name=\"Popularity of Noah in the United States\">[http://www.ssa.gov/OACT/babynames/top5names.html Popularity of Noah in the United States]</ref>\nIn 2013 it was the third [[List of most popular given names#Male names 5|most popular name for boys in Australia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://parenting.kidspot.com.au/australias-100-most-popular-baby-names/#.Us8-yqxBRPh|title=Australia\u2019s 100 most popular baby names|publisher=Kidspot|date=April 2, 2013|accessdate=2014-01-10|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110091657/http://parenting.kidspot.com.au/australias-100-most-popular-baby-names/#.Us8-yqxBRPh|archivedate=January 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Variants in other languages==\n* [[Arabic language|Arabic]]: \u0646\u064f\u0648\u062d\u0652 (''N\u016b\u1e25'')\n* [[Armenian language|Armenian]]: \u0546\u0578\u0575 (''Noy'')\n* [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]]: \u041d\u043e\u0439 (''Noy'')\n* [[Catalan language|Catalan]]: No\u00e8\n* [[Czech language|Czech]]: Noe\n* [[Dutch language|Dutch]]: No\u00eb\n* [[Finnish language|Finnish]]: Nooa\n* [[French language|French]]: No\u00e9\n* [[Georgian language|Georgian]]: \u10dc\u10dd\u10d4 (''Noe'')\n* [[Greek language|Greek]]: \u039d\u03ce\u03b5 (''No\u00e9'')\n* [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]]: \u05e0\u05b9\u05d7\u05b7 (''Noakh'')\n* [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]]: No\u00e9\n* [[Italian language|Italian]]: No\u00e8\n* [[Icelandic language|Icelandic]]: N\u00f3i\n* [[Latvian language|Latvian]]: Noass\n* [[Lithuanian language|Lithuanian]]: Nojus\n* [[Polish language|Polish]]: Noe\n* [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]: No\u00e9\n* [[Romanian language|Romanian]]: Noe\n* [[Russian language|Russian]]: \u041d\u043e\u0439 (''Noy'')\n* [[Spanish language|Spanish]]: No\u00e9\n* [[Serbian language|Serbian]]: Noje (''Noye'')\n