{"title_page": "Ten Percent Ring", "text_new": "The '''Ten-Percent Ring''' was a title given by the editors of ''[[The Tombstone Epitaph]]'' in 1881 to [[Johnny Behan]] and his friends for stealing about ten percent of the local [[Tombstone, Arizona]] taxes in the 1880s. Milt Joyce (1847-1889), owner of the Oriental Saloon and chairman of [[Cochise County, Arizona]] supervisors was also seen as a leader of the Ten Percent Ring. The ''Tombstone Epitaph'' was started by [[John Clum]] in 1880. <ref>The Tombstone Epitaph, December 25, 1881.</ref> The newspaper outlined the corruption charges of Johnny Behan the Cochise County [[sheriff]]. <ref>James Covington Hancock Papers, Arizona Historical Society, Tucson.</ref> <ref>Wyatt Earp: A Vigilante Life, Andrew C. Isenberg page 241</ref> When Johnny Behan was the Cochise County sheriff one of his duties was collecting prostitution, gambling, liquor, and theater taxes. As part of his pay, he received 10% of all proceeds collected. There was much talk in the town about the [[Graft (politics)|graft]] [[political corruption]] of the sheriff. For this many saw Behan as the head of the Ten Percent Ring and a friend of the outlaw [[Cochise County Cowboys]]. Others accused of membership in the ring was Artemus Fay (?-1906), owner of the Tombstone's first newspaper, the Tombstone ''Weekly Nugget'' and Harry Wood (1848-896) a writer for the ''Weekly Nugget'' and an under-sheriff of Behan.<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/70424429/harry-m-woods Find a grave, Harry M Woods]</ref> Behan so focused on taxes, that he was very soft on crime. Soon after Behan became sheriff, [[Virgil Earp]] was appointed Tombstone city marshal and had is brothers [[Wyatt Earp]] and [[Morgan Earp]] become special deputy policemen. Behan and the Earps were at conflict as Behan supported the outlaw [[Ike Clanton|Clanton]] and [[Frank McLaury|McLaury]] families.<ref>{{cite book|last=Urban|first=William|title=Wyatt Earp: The O.K. Corral and the Law of the American West |year=2003|publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group, Inc|url=https://archive.org/details/wyattearpokcorra00urba|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/wyattearpokcorra00urba/page/67 67]}}</ref><ref name=butler /> On January 31, 1882, Behan was arrested for collecting bills totaling $300 twice, arraigned in front of [[William Henry Stilwell|Justice Stilwell]], and discharged due to a technicality.<ref name=union14140>{{cite web|publisher=Sacramento Daily Union|volume=14 |number=140 |date=2 February 1882 |accessdate=16 October 2014 |title=Discharged from Custody Cowboys Surrendered|url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SDU18820202.2.7.3&srpos=48&e=-------en--20--41--txt-txIN-tombstone+earp------#}}</ref> Behan failed to win re-election as sheriff in November of 1882, he would not serve as a peace officer again. He later was appointed as the warden of the [[Yuma Territorial Prison]] and had various other government jobs until his death in 1912.<ref>[https://www.geni.com/people/Johnny-Behan-Sheriff-Cochise-County-Arizona-Territory/6000000010967709781 geni.com Johnny Behan] </ref><ref>Murder in Tombstone: The Forgotten Trial of Wyatt Earp, By Steven Lubet, page 38</ref><ref>I Meet Mrs. Earp, I Married Wyatt Earp, by Josephine Sarah Marcus Earp. Edited by Glenn G. Boyer. Tucson: University of Arizona Press, 1976.</ref><ref name=butler>{{cite book|last=Butler|first=Anne M.|title=Daughters of Joy, Sisters of Misery: Prostitutes in the American West, 1865\u201390|year=1987|publisher=University of Illinois Press|location=Urbana, Ill.|isbn=978-0-252-01466-6|edition=paperback|url=https://archive.org/details/daughtersofjoysi00butl}}</ref><ref>Doc Holliday: The Life and Legend, By Gary L. Roberts, page </ref> Milt Joyce, departed Tombstone in 1883. On October 10, 1880 Joyce and [[Doc Holliday]] had a shoot out at the Oriental. Joyce died in 1889 at the age of 42 in [[San Francisco]], he was the owner of the Baldwin Billiard Parlor in 1883 and later the Cafe Royal in San Francisco.<ref>[http://www.americancowboychronicles.com/2019/12/milt-joyce-western-pioneer.html americancowboychronicles.com Milt Joyce]</ref><ref>The Daily Alta California, November 30th, 1889</ref>  After Artemus Fay departed the ''Weekly Nugget'' he worked at the Nugget Mine in [[Dos Cabezas, Arizona|Dos Cabezas]] and start a short-lived paper there, the ''Gold Note''. After the death of his wife, Fay moved to [[Flagstaff, Arizona|Flagstaff]] and started a newspaper there.<ref>Tombstone, A.T.: A History of Early Mining, Milling, and Mayhem, By Wm. B. Shillingberg, page 205</ref>\n\n==Popular culture==\nThe Ten Percent Ring was a key figure in the much-fictionized TV series ''[[The Life and Legend of Wyatt Earp]]'', starring [[Hugh O'Brian]] in the starring role. [[Steve Brodie (actor)|Steve Brodie]] played Behan in nine episodes of the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0479017/?ref_=tt_cl_t9|title=Lash LaRue|publisher=[[Internet Movie Data Base]]|accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Gunfight at the O.K. Corral]]\n*[[Confederate Arizona]]\n*[[Arizona Territory in the American Civil War]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Wild West}}\n{{Cochise County Conflict}}\n\n\n[[Category:History of Cochise County, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Arizona folklore]]\n[[Category:Crime in Arizona Territory]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1881]]\n[[Category:Cochise County conflict]]\n[[Category:Outlaws of the American Old West]]\n[[Category:Gangs in Arizona]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Ten-Percent Ring''' was a title given by the editors of ''[[The Tombstone Epitaph]]'' in 1881 to [[Johnny Behan]] and his friends for stealing about ten percent of the local [[Tombstone, Arizona]] taxes in the 1880s. Milt Joyce (1847-1889), owner of the Oriental Saloon and chairman of [[Cochise County, Arizona]] supervisors was also seen as a leader of the Ten Percent Ring. The ''Tombstone Epitaph'' was started by [[John Clum]] in 1880. <ref>The Tombstone Epitaph, December 25, 1881.</ref> The newspaper outlined the corruption charges of Johnny Behan the Cochise County [[sheriff]]. <ref>James Covington Hancock Papers, Arizona Historical Society, Tucson.</ref> <ref>Wyatt Earp: A Vigilante Life, Andrew C. Isenberg page 241</ref> When Johnny Behan was the Cochise County sheriff one of his duties was collecting prostitution, gambling, liquor, and theater taxes. As part of his pay, he received 10% of all proceeds collected. There was much talk in the town about the [[Graft (politics)|graft]] [[political corruption]] of the sheriff. For this many saw Behan as the head of the Ten Percent Ring and a friend of the outlaw [[Cochise County Cowboys]]. Others accused of membership in the ring was Artemus Fay (?-1906), owner of the Tombstone's first newspaper, the Tombstone ''Weekly Nugget'' and Harry Wood (1848-896) a writer for the ''Weekly Nugget'' and an under-sheriff of Behan.<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/70424429/harry-m-woods Find a grave, Harry M Woods]</ref> Behan so focused on taxes, that he was very soft on crime. Soon after Behan became sheriff, [[Virgil Earp]] was appointed Tombstone city marshal and had is brothers [[Wyatt Earp]] and [[Morgan Earp]] become special deputy policemen. Behan and the Earps were at conflict as Behan supported the outlaw [[Ike Clanton|Clanton]] and [[Frank McLaury|McLaury]] families.<ref>{{cite book|last=Urban|first=William|title=Wyatt Earp: The O.K. Corral and the Law of the American West |year=2003|publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group, Inc|url=https://archive.org/details/wyattearpokcorra00urba|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/wyattearpokcorra00urba/page/67 67]}}</ref><ref name=butler /> On January 31, 1882, Behan was arrested for collecting bills totaling $300 twice, arraigned in front of [[William Henry Stilwell|Justice Stilwell]], and discharged due to a technicality.<ref name=union14140>{{cite web|publisher=Sacramento Daily Union|volume=14 |number=140 |date=2 February 1882 |accessdate=16 October 2014 |title=Discharged from Custody Cowboys Surrendered|url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SDU18820202.2.7.3&srpos=48&e=-------en--20--41--txt-txIN-tombstone+earp------#}}</ref> Behan failed to win re-election as sheriff in November of 1882, he would not serve as a peace officer again. He later was appointed as the warden of the [[Yuma Territorial Prison]] and had various other government jobs until his death in 1912.<ref>[https://www.geni.com/people/Johnny-Behan-Sheriff-Cochise-County-Arizona-Territory/6000000010967709781 geni.com Johnny Behan] </ref><ref>Murder in Tombstone: The Forgotten Trial of Wyatt Earp, By Steven Lubet, page 38</ref><ref>I Meet Mrs. Earp, I Married Wyatt Earp, by Josephine Sarah Marcus Earp. Edited by Glenn G. Boyer. Tucson: University of Arizona Press, 1976.</ref><ref name=butler>{{cite book|last=Butler|first=Anne M.|title=Daughters of Joy, Sisters of Misery: Prostitutes in the American West, 1865\u201390|year=1987|publisher=University of Illinois Press|location=Urbana, Ill.|isbn=978-0-252-01466-6|edition=paperback|url=https://archive.org/details/daughtersofjoysi00butl}}</ref><ref>Doc Holliday: The Life and Legend, By Gary L. Roberts, page </ref> Milt Joyce, departed Tombstone in 1883. On October 10, 1880 Joyce and [[Doc Holliday]] had a shoot out at the Oriental. Joyce died in 1889 at the age of 42 in [[San Francisco]], he was the owner of the Baldwin Billiard Parlor in 1883 and later the Cafe Royal in San Francisco.<ref>[http://www.americancowboychronicles.com/2019/12/milt-joyce-western-pioneer.html americancowboychronicles.com Milt Joyce]</ref><ref>The Daily Alta California, November 30th, 1889</ref>  After Artemus Fay departed the ''Weekly Nugget'' he worked at the Nugget Mine in Dos Cabezas and start a short-lived paper there, the ''Gold Note''. After the death of his wife, Fay moved to Flagstaff and started a newspaper there.<ref>Tombstone, A.T.: A History of Early Mining, Milling, and Mayhem, By Wm. B. Shillingberg, page 205</ref>\n\n==Popular culture==\nThe Ten Percent Ring was a key figure in the much-fictionized TV series ''[[The Life and Legend of Wyatt Earp]]'', starring [[Hugh O'Brian]] in the starring role. [[Steve Brodie (actor)|Steve Brodie]] played Behan in nine episodes of the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0479017/?ref_=tt_cl_t9|title=Lash LaRue|publisher=[[Internet Movie Data Base]]|accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Gunfight at the O.K. Corral]]\n*[[Confederate Arizona]]\n*[[Arizona Territory in the American Civil War]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Wild West}}\n{{Cochise County Conflict}}\n\n\n[[Category:History of Cochise County, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Arizona folklore]]\n[[Category:Crime in Arizona Territory]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1881]]\n[[Category:Cochise County conflict]]\n[[Category:Outlaws of the American Old West]]\n[[Category:Gangs in Arizona]]\n", "name_user": "Telecineguy", "label": "safe", "comment": "link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ten_Percent_Ring"}
{"title_page": "Polish minority in the Republic of Ireland", "text_new": "{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group    = Poles in Ireland <br /> Polacy w Irlandii \n|population  ='''122,515 <br /> (2.57% of total population)''' (2016)\n|popplace = All over Ireland, especially [[Limerick]], [[Dublin]], [[Portlaoise]], [[Cork (city)|Cork]], [[Waterford]] and [[Galway]].\n|langs    = [[Polish language|Polish]], [[English language|English]]\n}}\n\n[[Image:Polish shop dublin.jpg|thumb|A Polish shop in [[Dublin]]]]\n\nThe '''Polish minority in the Republic of Ireland''' numbered approximately 122,515 (2.57% of the population) according to 2016 census figures.<ref>[http://www.cso.ie/en/media/csoie/releasespublications/documents/population/2017/Chapter_5_Diversity.pdf Census 2016 ]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420234900/http://www.cso.ie/en/media/csoie/releasespublications/documents/population/2017/Chapter_5_Diversity.pdf |date=April 20, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:PPS numbers for Poles (2001-2010).png|thumb|Chart tracking the number of Polish applicants for [[Personal Public Service Number|Irish PPS numbers]] between 2001 and 2010]]\nAfter [[Poland]] joined the [[European Union]] in May 2004, [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] was one of just three existing EU members to open its borders and welcome Polish workers (the others being the [[United Kingdom]] and [[Sweden]]). Ireland quickly became a key destination for Poles wishing to work outside the country; in 2004 a website advertising Irish jobs in [[Polish language|Polish]] received over 170,000 hits in its first day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2004/0519/internet-business.html|title=New Irish jobsite a hit in Poland|date=19 May 2004|work=RT\u00c9.ie|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref> During the 2007 [[2007 Polish parliamentary election|Polish general election]], Polish parties campaigned in Ireland and three voting locations were set up; in Dublin, [[Cork (city)|Cork]], and [[Limerick]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2007/0930/poland.html|title=Polish opposition party campaigns in Ireland|date=30 September 2007|work=RT\u00c9.ie|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the period immediately following the [[Post-2008 Irish economic downturn|2008 economic downturn]], the number of Polish people in Ireland declined,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.finfacts.ie/irishfinancenews/article_1015464.shtml|title=Up to 1,300 Polish people leaving Ireland every week|publisher=|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref> with some reports suggesting that 30,000 were leaving Ireland per year,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/business/irish/poles-flee-ailing-irish-economy-1511401.html|title=Poles flee ailing Irish economy|work=Independent.ie|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref> and the [[Central Statistics Office (Ireland)|Central Statistics Office]] reporting a decrease in the number of Polish people applying for [[Personal Public Service Number|PPS numbers]].<ref>[http://www.cso.ie/releasespublications/documents/labour_market/current/ppsn.pdf CSO - Foreign Nationals: PPSN Allocations, Employment and Social Welfare Activity - 2009]</ref>\n\n== Language and media ==\nPolish, although not officially an established subject, can be taken as part of the Irish [[Irish Leaving Certificate|Leaving Certificate]] examination as is the case with all official languages of the European Union. The exam used is based on the paper of the [[European Baccalaureate]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.examinations.ie/index.php?l=en&mc=ex&sc=eu|title=State Examination Commission - Examination Information|publisher=|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref> The biggest Polish umbrella organization is Polish Educational Society in Ireland (PESI), a non-profit organisation established in 2012.<ref>http://www.polskamacierz.com/english.html</ref> PESI sponsors Polish supplementary schools in Ireland and widely cooperates with Polish government bodies and organisations working for the maintenance and promotion of Polish language abroad. \n\nThe large number of Poles in Ireland led to the provision of a number of media outlets catering to them. Newspapers: \"Nasz Glos\" (Our Voice) is a Polish weekly freesheet distributed across Ireland;<ref>http://www.ng24.ie</ref> ''Polska Gazeta''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polskagazeta.ie|title=Polska Gazeta - NAJWI\u0118KSZY POLSKI TYGODNIK W IRLANDII OD 2005 ROKU|publisher=|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref> and a section in Dublin's [[Evening Herald]] entitled \"''Polski'' Herald\". Dublin cable television channel, [[City Channel (Dublin)|City Channel]], also features a programme aimed at Poles in Ireland entitled Oto Polska (This is Poland).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://networkeurope.radio.cz/feature/polish-language-tv-helping-irelands-fastest-growing-immigrant-group-feel-at-home|title=Polish language TV helping Ireland\u2019s fastest growing immigrant group feel at home|publisher=|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nOther online media in Ireland:\n* [http://www.gazeta.ie www.gazeta.ie] - the largest website of Polish community in Dublin area \n* [http://www.ng24.ie www.ng24.ie] - the official website of \"Nasz G\u0142os\" The Free Polish Weekly \n* [http://www.galway.pl Galway.pl] - the largest website of Polish community in the West of Ireland\n* [http://www.nadajemy.ie Nadajemy.ie] - the biggest social networking website for Polish people in Ireland\n* [http://www.mycork.org Mycork.org] - the first Polish forum in Ireland and website of Polish community in Cork\n* [http://www.polish-chaplaincy.ie/ Polish-chaplaincy.ie] - a website of  Polish chaplaincy in Dublin\n* [http://www.luteranie.pl/dublin Polish Lutherans] - a website of Polish Lutherans in Ireland\n* [https://abcedulibrary.ie/en/ ABC EduLibrary]- Polish library in Cork (not only for Polish!)\n* [http://www.together-razem.org Together-Razem Centre] - the first Polish charity in Ireland website\n\n==Notable people==\n{{further information|:Category:Irish people of Polish descent}}\nRafal H\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Ireland|Poland}}\n* [[Ireland\u2013Poland relations]]\n* [[Polish diaspora|Polonia]]\n* [[Polish migration to the United Kingdom]]\n* [[Soupy Norman]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Polish diaspora}}\n{{Immigration to the Republic of Ireland}}\n\n[[Category:Polish minorities|Ireland]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Ireland]]\n[[Category:Irish people of Polish descent| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group    = Poles in Ireland <br /> Polacy w Irlandii \n|population  ='''122,515 <br /> (2.57% of total population)''' (2016)\n|popplace = All over Ireland, especially [[Limerick]], [[Dublin]], [[Portlaoise]], [[Cork (city)|Cork]], [[Waterford]] and [[Galway]].\n|langs    = [[Polish language|Polish]], [[English language|English]]\n}}\n\n[[Image:Polish shop dublin.jpg|thumb|A Polish shop in [[Dublin]]]]\n\nThe '''Polish minority in the Republic of Ireland''' numbered approximately 122,515 (2.57% of the population) according to 2016 census figures.<ref>[http://www.cso.ie/en/media/csoie/releasespublications/documents/population/2017/Chapter_5_Diversity.pdf Census 2016 ]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420234900/http://www.cso.ie/en/media/csoie/releasespublications/documents/population/2017/Chapter_5_Diversity.pdf |date=April 20, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:PPS numbers for Poles (2001-2010).png|thumb|Chart tracking the number of Polish applicants for [[Personal Public Service Number|Irish PPS numbers]] between 2001 and 2010]]\nAfter [[Poland]] joined the [[European Union]] in May 2004, [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] was one of just three existing EU members to open its borders and welcome Polish workers (the others being the [[United Kingdom]] and [[Sweden]]). Ireland quickly became a key destination for Poles wishing to work outside the country; in 2004 a website advertising Irish jobs in [[Polish language|Polish]] received over 170,000 hits in its first day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2004/0519/internet-business.html|title=New Irish jobsite a hit in Poland|date=19 May 2004|work=RT\u00c9.ie|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref> During the 2007 [[2007 Polish parliamentary election|Polish general election]], Polish parties campaigned in Ireland and three voting locations were set up; in Dublin, [[Cork (city)|Cork]], and [[Limerick]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2007/0930/poland.html|title=Polish opposition party campaigns in Ireland|date=30 September 2007|work=RT\u00c9.ie|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the period immediately following the [[Post-2008 Irish economic downturn|2008 economic downturn]], the number of Polish people in Ireland declined,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.finfacts.ie/irishfinancenews/article_1015464.shtml|title=Up to 1,300 Polish people leaving Ireland every week|publisher=|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref> with some reports suggesting that 30,000 were leaving Ireland per year,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/business/irish/poles-flee-ailing-irish-economy-1511401.html|title=Poles flee ailing Irish economy|work=Independent.ie|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref> and the [[Central Statistics Office (Ireland)|Central Statistics Office]] reporting a decrease in the number of Polish people applying for [[Personal Public Service Number|PPS numbers]].<ref>[http://www.cso.ie/releasespublications/documents/labour_market/current/ppsn.pdf CSO - Foreign Nationals: PPSN Allocations, Employment and Social Welfare Activity - 2009]</ref>\n\n== Language and media ==\nPolish, although not officially an established subject, can be taken as part of the Irish [[Irish Leaving Certificate|Leaving Certificate]] examination as is the case with all official languages of the European Union. The exam used is based on the paper of the [[European Baccalaureate]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.examinations.ie/index.php?l=en&mc=ex&sc=eu|title=State Examination Commission - Examination Information|publisher=|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref> The biggest Polish umbrella organization is Polish Educational Society in Ireland (PESI), a non-profit organisation established in 2012.<ref>http://www.polskamacierz.com/english.html</ref> PESI sponsors Polish supplementary schools in Ireland and widely cooperates with Polish government bodies and organisations working for the maintenance and promotion of Polish language abroad. \n\nThe large number of Poles in Ireland led to the provision of a number of media outlets catering to them. Newspapers: \"Nasz Glos\" (Our Voice) is a Polish weekly freesheet distributed across Ireland;<ref>http://www.ng24.ie</ref> ''Polska Gazeta''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polskagazeta.ie|title=Polska Gazeta - NAJWI\u0118KSZY POLSKI TYGODNIK W IRLANDII OD 2005 ROKU|publisher=|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref> and a section in Dublin's [[Evening Herald]] entitled \"''Polski'' Herald\". Dublin cable television channel, [[City Channel (Dublin)|City Channel]], also features a programme aimed at Poles in Ireland entitled Oto Polska (This is Poland).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://networkeurope.radio.cz/feature/polish-language-tv-helping-irelands-fastest-growing-immigrant-group-feel-at-home|title=Polish language TV helping Ireland\u2019s fastest growing immigrant group feel at home|publisher=|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nOther online media in Ireland:\n* [http://www.gazeta.ie www.gazeta.ie] - the largest website of Polish community in Dublin area \n* [http://www.ng24.ie www.ng24.ie] - the official website of \"Nasz G\u0142os\" The Free Polish Weekly \n* [http://www.galway.pl Galway.pl] - the largest website of Polish community in the West of Ireland\n* [http://www.nadajemy.ie Nadajemy.ie] - the biggest social networking website for Polish people in Ireland\n* [http://www.mycork.org Mycork.org] - the first Polish forum in Ireland and website of Polish community in Cork\n* [http://www.polish-chaplaincy.ie/ Polish-chaplaincy.ie] - a website of  Polish chaplaincy in Dublin\n* [http://www.luteranie.pl/dublin Polish Lutherans] - a website of Polish Lutherans in Ireland\n* [https://abcedulibrary.ie/en/ ABC EduLibrary]- Polish library in Cork (not only for Polish!)\n* [http://www.together-razem.org Together-Razem Centre] - the first Polish charity in Ireland website\n\n==Notable people==\n{{further information|:Category:Irish people of Polish descent}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Ireland|Poland}}\n* [[Ireland\u2013Poland relations]]\n* [[Polish diaspora|Polonia]]\n* [[Polish migration to the United Kingdom]]\n* [[Soupy Norman]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Polish diaspora}}\n{{Immigration to the Republic of Ireland}}\n\n[[Category:Polish minorities|Ireland]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Ireland]]\n[[Category:Irish people of Polish descent| ]]\n", "name_user": "37.228.253.184", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polish_minority_in_the_Republic_of_Ireland"}
{"title_page": "John Ferdinand Smyth Stuart", "text_new": "[[File:Ferdinand Smyth Stuart.jpeg|thumb|Ferdinand Smyth Stuart, 1808]]\n'''John Ferdinand Smyth Stuart''' (1745 \u2013 20 December 1814), known until 1793 as '''John Ferdinand Smyth''' and mostly after that as '''Ferdinand Smyth Stuart''', was a Scottish-born American [[Loyalists fighting in the American Revolution|loyalist]] and physician who claimed to be a great-grandson of [[Charles II of England|King Charles II]]. As the author of ''A Tour in the United States of America'' (1784), he used the name '''John Ferdinand Dalziel Smyth'''. \n\nLeaving America during the Revolutionary War, Stuart spent the rest of his life in England and the West Indies.\n==Background and early life==\nStuart was born in Scotland in 1745 and began life there as John Smyth or John Ferdinand Smyth. He later wrote that he was the son of R. Wentworth Smyth, a Jacobite who had fought in the risings of [[Jacobite rising of 1715|1715]] and [[Jacobite rising of 1745|1745]]. According to Stuart\u2019s account, in 1744 his father was sixty-six and married Maria Julia Dalziel, a girl of fifteen, as his second wife. He reported that his mother was a grand-daughter of [[James Crofts (British Army officer)|General James Crofts]], a natural son of the [[James Scott, 1st Duke of Monmouth|Duke of Monmouth]], a son of Charles II, and that his father was Monmouth\u2019s natural son by Henrietta Maria Wentworth, a daughter of [[Thomas Wentworth, 5th Baron Wentworth|Thomas, Lord Wentworth]], and grand-daughter of [[Thomas Wentworth, 1st Earl of Cleveland]]. Henrietta Maria had died in 1686, not long after Monmouth's execution, and her son Wentworth had been adopted by a Colonel Smyth, an [[aide-de-camp]] of Monmouth, becoming the Colonel\u2019s heir.<ref name=dnb>[[Edward Irving Carlyle]], \u201cStuart, John Ferdinand Smyth\u201d, in ''[[Dictionary of National Biography]] 1885-1900'', Vol. 55</ref> Consequently, Stuart\u2019s father grew up in France. He returned to Scotland at the time of the 1715 Rising.<ref name=monthly>\u201cMemoirs of FERDINAND SMYTH STUART, M.D., Major in the British Army, and Grandson of the Duke of Monmouth\u201d, in ''The Monthly Magazine'', 1 February 1815, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6m76vtrNAJkC&pg=PA36#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 36\u201341]</ref> Stuart stated in 1808 that he was named after his godfather, [[Duke Ferdinand of Brunswick-Wolfenb\u00fcttel|Prince  Ferdinand of Brunswick]].<ref>Ferdinand  Smyth Stuart, ''Destiny and Fortitude'' (1808) p. 42</ref> A genealogist, [[Anthony J. Camp]], has cast doubts on this account.<ref name=AJC>[[Anthony J. Camp]], [http://anthonyjcamp.com/page20.htm John Ferdinand Smyth: loyalist and liar] at anthonyjcamp.com, as published in ''Genealogists' Magazine'', vol. 31, no. 11 (September 2015)</ref> On Henrietta Maria Wentworth, [[Allan Fea]] was convinced that Monmouth \u201dundoubtedly left a son by her (born in 1681), who was adopted and educated in Paris by Colonel Smyth\u201d, but no evidence of the existence of Maria Julia Dalziel has yet come to light.<ref name=AJC/>\n\nStuart recalled being orphaned by the death of his mother when he was two and his father when he was five, his father being drowned in a river, after falling off a bridge during an attempt to arrest him.<ref name=monthly/> According to Stuart, he was \u201cbred to Physic and was at one of the Scotch Universities\u201d and migrated from London to Virginia in 1763.<ref name=AJC/> An obituary  said that Stuart had been a Doctor of Medicine and had been educated \u201camid the Grampian hills\u201d, before attending the lectures of [[John Gregory (moralist)|Dr Gregory]] at Aberdeen,<ref name=monthly/> but no university career has been traced.<ref name=AJC/>\n\n==Life in America==\nStuart emigrated to the [[Thirteen Colonies]] and settled near [[Williamsburg, Virginia|Williamsburg]] in the [[Colony of Virginia]], where he later practised as a physician. By the 1770s, he had became a planter, renting plantations rather than owning them.<ref name=AJC/> The [[American Revolutionary War]] broke out, and on 15 October 1775, as a loyalist to Great Britain, Smyth quitted Virginia and joined the [[Loyalists fighting in the American Revolution|Loyalist forces]]. He served in several regiments in the rank of captain. He later wrote that at one time he commanded an armed sloop in [[Chesapeake Bay]] and at another raised a company of men for frontier work. More than once he was taken prisoner, and was shackled for eighteen months.<ref name=dnb/>\n\nAt New York, at about the end of 1777, Captain Smyth wrote his ''Narrative or Journal of Capt. John Ferdinand Dalziel Smyth, of the Queen's Rangers'', setting out his adventures, and was critical of the \u201cdeluded and mistaken\u201d rebels. This was printed in 1778.<ref>''Narrative or Journal of Capt. John Ferdinand Dalziel Smyth, of the Queen's Rangers'', reprinted in ''The Pennsylvania Magazine of History and Biography'', Vol. 39, No. 2 (1915), pp. 143-169</ref> He was then an officer of the [[Queen's Rangers]], a Loyalist regiment stationed at King's Bridge, New York, from July 1778.<ref name=AJC/> On 23 October 1778, he married Abigail Haugewout, the daughter of a loyalist farmer in Hempstead, on [[Long Island]], and their daughter Elizabeth was born in 1780.<ref name=hofstra/>\n\nStuart had leave to be absent from [[Muster (military)|musters]] in August and October 1778, but he was on duty in February 1779. In May 1779 he brought proceedings on various grounds against his commanding officer, Lieutenant-Colonel [[John Graves Simcoe]], but they were found to be \u201cMalicious, Frivolous, Vexatious, & Groundless\u201d. Simcoe claimed that Captain Smyth \u201cavoided military service whenever possible\u201d. He was sick in quarters at a muster on 24 June 1779, and not far into 1780, he returned to England, on the grounds of ill health.<ref name=AJC/>\n\n==England and West Indies==\nStuart remained an officer on half-pay for the duration of the American War. Commissioners had been appointed to assist loyalists who had suffered losses by the war, and in 1780 they awarded Stuart a temporary allowance of \u00a3100 a year, increasing this to \u00a3200 in 1781 and to \u00a3300 in 1783. He made an application to the Privy Council to be granted [[Long Island, Bahamas|Long Island]] in [[the Bahamas]], in view of his claimed losses of 3,300 acres in Virginia and Maryland, but he was not believed and this was rejected. His half-pay came to an end in 1783.<ref name=AJC/>\n\nIn 1784, allegations were made against Stuart to the claims commissioners, and his allowance was suspended. Stuart then wrote his book ''A Tour in the United States of America'',<ref name=dnb/> which was published by [[George Robinson (1737\u20131801)|George Robinson]] in 1784, agreeing to pay \u00a3160 for the printing. This, however, brought his account of himself to a wide public, and people who had known him in North America challenged it.<ref name=AJC/> \n\nIn 1785, Stuart went out to Jamaica, where he was appointed a Major \u201cin that Island only\u201d, but only remained there for sixteen days, as the result of a [[hurricane]].<ref name=AJC/>\n\nIn 1793, he adopted the name of Stuart, to mark his claim to descent from the [[House of Stuart]], and went on arguing his case to the government, without success.<ref name=dnb/>\n\nIn 1795, Stuart accepted a post as assistant barrack-master-general in [[San Domingo]] and to get there joined [[Admiral (Royal Navy)|Admiral]] [[Hugh Cloberry Christian|Sir Hugh Cloberry Christian]] on an expedition to the [[West Indies]]. He was shipwrecked three times in 1795 and 1796 and was present at the British capture of [[Saint Lucia]] and [[Martinique]]. In San Domingo, although not employed as a medical officer, he prescribed five grains of tartarised antimony and a tablespoonful of soft sugar for the treatment of [[yellow fever]], later claiming that this had proved a good treatment.<ref name=monthly/> On his return to England, Stuart continued to pursue his financial claims unsuccessfully, but continued to write in support of them.<ref name=dnb/>\n\nIn 1803, while Stuart was barrack-master at [[Billericay]], he suffered a severe beating which knocked out several of his teeth. In the final years of his life, he was barrack-master at [[Landguard Fort]], near [[Felixstowe]] in Suffolk. In 1814, Stuart retired from this work and settled in Vernon Place, [[Bloomsbury Square]].<ref name=monthly/>\n\n==Marriages and death==\nOn 23 October 1778, while he was Captain Smyth of the [[Queen's Rangers]], against her father\u2019s wishes Stuart married Abigail Haugewout, the 23-year-old daughter of Leffert Haugewout, a loyalist farmer of [[Hempstead (village), New York|Hempstead, New York]]. They set up house in [[Oyster Bay (town), New York|Oyster Bay]] and had one daughter, Elizabeth, born in October 1780, but by then Smyth had gone to live in England. His pregnant wife did not go with him and lived on until 1828, on a farm of fifteen acres in Hempstead which her father gave her. In 1797, Stuart returned on a visit and met his wife in New York. In 1802, his daughter Elizabeth married Gideon Nichols, a Hempstead merchant.<ref name=hofstra>[https://www.hofstra.edu/pdf/library/libspc_lisi_hart_nichols_fa.pdf Hart Nichols Collection, 1730-1930] at hofstra.edu (Special Collections Department, Long Island Studies Institute), pp. 4, 5, 10, 32: \u201dUpon her father\u2019s return to America seventeen years later, a relationship developed with him and his children from his second wife Eunice Grey (c1776-1818). This union created seven half brothers and sisters. They were Henry Stuart Smyth Stuart (1793-1794), Henrietta Maria Stuart Smyth Stuart (1797-1813), Mary Clementina Stuart Smyth Stuart (c1799-1826), Charles Henry Stuart Smyth Stuart (1802-1802), Constantine Wentworth Stuart Smyth Stuart (1805-1849), Spencer Percival Stuart Smyth Stuart (1807-c1807), and Ferdinand Stuart Smyth Stuart (c1812-1835).\u201d</ref>\n\nBefore his return to New York in 1797, Stuart had begun a second family in England with Eunice Gray, a girl of about sixteen. \nTheir son Henry was born in 1793, their first daughter, Henrietta Maria, in 1797,<ref>[https://www.ancestry.co.uk/interactive/1624/31280_199044-00310 Stuart \u2014 Henrietta Maria daughter of John Ferdinand Dalziel and Eunice] at ancestry.co.uk, accessed 21 April 2020 {{subscription}}</ref> and another daughter, Mary Clementina, about 1799, then another son, Charles Henry, in 1802.<ref name=hofstra/> On 7 September 1803, Stuart married Eunice Gray, at [[St Martin-in-the-Fields]], Westminster.<ref>\u201cJohn Ferdinand Dalziel Smyth Stuart and Eunice Gray, Marriage07/09/1803 Saint Martin in the  Fields, Westminster, London\u201c at ancestry.co.uk, accessed 21 April 2020 {{subscription}}</ref> Their third son, Constantine Wentworth, was born in August 1805,<ref>[https://www.ancestry.co.uk/interactive/1624/31280_199042-00424 \u201cConstantine Wentworth Stuart\u201d] baptism at ancestry.co.uk, accessed 21 April 2020, gives a date of birth, 11 August 1805, as well as a date of baptism, 9 September 1805 {{subscription}}</ref> a fourth, Spencer Percival, in 1807,<ref>[https://www.ancestry.co.uk/interactive/1624/31280_199042-00432 Spencer Percival Stuart. Son of Ferdinand and Eunice Smyth Stuart] baptism at ancestry.co.uk, accessed 21 April 2020, gives a date of birth, 14 June 1805, as well as a date of baptism, 14 July 1807 {{subscription}}</ref> and a fifth and last son, Ferdinand, in 1812. As a result of Stuart\u2019s visit to New York in 1797, his daughter Elizabeth at Hempstead was in contact with her new relations in England. Four of the children in England died young: Henry in 1794, Charles Henry in 1802, Spencer Percival about 1807, and Henrietta Maria in 1813,<ref name=hofstra/> just after her 16th birthday.<ref name=monthly/>\n\nOn 20 December 1814, Stuart was run over and killed by a carriage which hit him at the corner of [[Southampton Street, London|Southampton Street]], central London, leaving his second family destitute.<ref>[[Notes and Queries]], 2nd series, VIII, p. 495, IX, pp. 232, 334</ref> He was buried on 1 January 1815 at [[Marylebone]], where the parish register notes that he was of St George\u2019s parish, [[Bloomsbury]].<ref>''Burials in the Parish of St Mary-le-Bone'',  [https://www.ancestry.co.uk/interactive/1559/31280_194703-00275 p. 2] at ancestry.co.uk, accessed 21 April 2020 {{subscription}}</ref> A six-page obituary in the [[Monthly Magazine]] celebrated Stuart\u2019s life and appealed on behalf of his dependants \n{{Quote|\u201cIt may be hoped that some friend of the royal house of Guelph will do Humanity the justice to  point out to them the necessities of this withered branch of the once-royal house of Stuart.\u201d<ref name=monthly/>}}\n\nIn January 1815, [[Lord Palmerston]], Secretary for War, agreed to Eunice Stuart being paid an annual allowance of \u00a325 out of his Compassionate Fund, including \u00a315 for the support of her children. In June 1816, the [[George IV of the United Kingdom|Prince Regent]], the future George IV, granted Eunice a pension of \u00a350 a year from the [[Civil List]], to supplement the grant from the Compassionate Fund, which she reported to Palmerston. She died in 1818, and Palmerston increased the money paid for the children to \u00a324 a year. A neighbour paid Constantine Wentworth\u2019s education at [[Charterhouse School]], [[Smithfield, London|Smithfield]].<ref name=AJC/>\n\nTwo of Stuart\u2019s remaining children died in their twenties, Mary Clementina in 1826, and Ferdinand in 1835. Constantine Wentworth lived until 1849, and married. In July 1828, he was an officer in the [[6th Regiment of Foot]] and was promoted from Ensign to Lieutenant without purchase.<ref>\u201cEnsign Constantine Wentworth Stuart Smyth Stuart\u201d in ''[[The London Gazette]]'', Issue 18495, 12 August 1828, p. 1534, col. 1</ref> He resigned his commission at Poona, in 1832, and later visited his half-sister, Elizabeth, in Hempstead, New York.<ref name=AJC/> She had a number of children and grandchildren, lived until 1858, and left many descendants.<ref name=hofstra/>\n\n==Published works==\n*John Ferdinand Dalziel Smyth, ''Narrative or Journal of Capt. John Ferdinand Dalziel Smyth, of the Queen's Rangers'' (New York, 1778), is Stuart\u2019s first known substantial publication.<ref name=AJC/> \n*John Ferdinand Dalziel Smyth, ''A Tour in the United States of America'' (London, G. Robinson, 1784), a much longer work, describes Stuart\u2019s recent travels there and his activities during the War of Independence.<ref name=dnb/> The book was republished in 2010 in a 468-page paperback by [[Kessinger Publishing]] of [[Whitefish, Montana]], {{ISBN|978-1162797267}}. It was translated into French and in 1791 published by Buisson of Paris under the title ''Voyage dans les \u00c9tats-Unis de l'Am\u00e9rique, fait en 1784''.<ref> [https://openlibrary.org/books/OL25938880M/Voyage_dans_les_\u00c9tats-Unis_de_l'Am\u00e9rique_fait_en_1784 ''Voyage dans les \u00c9tats-Unis de l'Am\u00e9rique, fait en 1784'' at openlibrary.org</ref> Stuart\u2019s view of the country has been called \n{{Quote|\u201c...vigorous but not flattering. The republican opinions of the colonists were obnoxious to a loyalist, while their barbarous manners were repellent to a gentleman.\u201d<ref name=dnb/>}}\n* John Ferdinand Smyth Stuart, ''A Letter to Lord Henry Petty on Coercive Vaccination'' (London, 1807) is a forceful medical and political argument against [[vaccination]] addressed to [[Henry Petty-Fitzmaurice, 3rd Marquess of Lansdowne|Lord Henry Petty]], the youthful [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]].<ref>Chambers, Book of Days, vol. I, p. 628</ref> It was motivated by the death of one of his own children.<ref name=AJC/>\n*Ferdinand Smyth Stuart, ''The Case of Ferdinand Smyth Stuart'' (London, 1807) returned to Stuart\u2019s complaints about his treatment by the British government.<ref name=dnb/>\n*Ferdinand Smyth Stuart, ''Destiny and Fortitude: An Historical Poem: In Sixteen Elegies: Being a Detail of the Misfortunes of the Illustrious House of Stuart'' (London, 1808), followed shortly after the death of [[Henry Benedict Stuart]], the last legitimate Stuart descendant of [[James II of England|King James II]], and celebrated his own family\u2019s [[Jacobitism]].<ref name=dnb/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n==External links==\n*[https://www.worldcat.org/identities/lccn-n85247830/ Stuart, John Ferdinand Smyth 1745\u20131814] at [[WorldCat]]\n*[https://www.jstor.org/stable/20086210 ''Narrative or Journal of Capt. John Ferdinand Dalziel Smyth, of the Queen's Rangers'' (1778)], reprinted in ''The Pennsylvania Magazine of History and Biography'', Vol. 39, No. 2 (1915), in open [[JSTOR]] collections\n*[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6m76vtrNAJkC&pg=PA36 \u201cMemoirs of FERDINAND SMYTH STUART, M.D., Major in the British Army, and Grandson of the Duke of Monmouth\u201d], obituary in ''The Monthly Magazine'', 1 February 1815, pp. 36\u201341 \n*[http://anthonyjcamp.com/page20.htm John Ferdinand Smyth: loyalist and liar], by [[Anthony J. Camp]], at anthonyjcamp.com, as published in ''Genealogists' Magazine'', vol. 31, no. 11 (September 2015)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stuart, John Ferdinand Smyth}}\n[[Category:1745 births]]\n[[Category:1814 deaths]]\n[[Category:18th-century Scottish medical doctors]]\n[[Category:Loyalist military personnel of the American Revolutionary War]]\n[[Category:House of Stuart]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Ferdinand Smyth Stuart.jpeg|thumb|Ferdinand Smyth Stuart, 1808]]\n'''John Ferdinand Smyth Stuart''' (1745 \u2013 20 December 1814), known until 1793 as '''John Ferdinand Smyth''' and mostly after that as '''Ferdinand Smyth Stuart''', was a Scottish-born American [[Loyalists fighting in the American Revolution|loyalist]] and physician who claimed to be a great-grandson of [[Charles II of England|King Charles II]]. As the author of ''A Tour in the United States of America'' (1784), he used the name '''John Ferdinand Dalziel Smyth'''. \n\nLeaving America during the Revolutionary War, Stuart spent the rest of his life in England and the West Indies.\n==Background and early life==\nStuart was born in Scotland in 1745 and began life there as John Smyth or John Ferdinand Smyth. He later wrote that he was the son of R. Wentworth Smyth, a Jacobite who had fought in the risings of [[Jacobite rising of 1715|1715]] and [[Jacobite rising of 1745|1745]]. According to Stuart\u2019s account, in 1744 his father was sixty-six and married Maria Julia Dalziel, a girl of fifteen, as his second wife. He reported that his mother was a grand-daughter of [[James Crofts (British Army officer)|General James Crofts]], a natural son of the [[James Scott, 1st Duke of Monmouth|Duke of Monmouth]], a son of Charles II, and that his father was Monmouth\u2019s natural son by Henrietta Maria Wentworth, a daughter of [[Thomas Wentworth, 5th Baron Wentworth|Thomas, Lord Wentworth]], and grand-daughter of [[Thomas Wentworth, 1st Earl of Cleveland]]. Henrietta Maria had died in 1686, not long after Monmouth's execution, and her son Wentworth had been adopted by a Colonel Smyth, an [[aide-de-camp]] of Monmouth, becoming the Colonel\u2019s heir.<ref name=dnb>[[Edward Irving Carlyle]], \u201cStuart, John Ferdinand Smyth\u201d, in ''[[Dictionary of National Biography]] 1885-1900'', Vol. 55</ref> Consequently, Stuart\u2019s father grew up in France. He returned to Scotland at the time of the 1715 Rising.<ref name=monthly>\u201cMemoirs of FERDINAND SMYTH STUART, M.D., Major in the British Army, and Grandson of the Duke of Monmouth\u201d, in ''The Monthly Magazine'', 1 February 1815, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6m76vtrNAJkC&pg=PA36#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 36\u201341]</ref> Stuart stated in 1808 that he was named after his godfather, [[Duke Ferdinand of Brunswick-Wolfenb\u00fcttel|Prince  Ferdinand of Brunswick]].<ref>Ferdinand  Smyth Stuart, ''Destiny and Fortitude'' (1808) p. 42</ref> A genealogist, [[Anthony J. Camp]], has cast doubts on this account.<ref name=AJC>[[Anthony J. Camp]], [http://anthonyjcamp.com/page20.htm John Ferdinand Smyth: loyalist and liar] at anthonyjcamp.com, as published in ''Genealogists' Magazine'', vol. 31, no. 11 (September 2015)</ref> On Henrietta Maria Wentworth, [[Allan Fea]] was convinced that Monmouth \u201dundoubtedly left a son by her (born in 1681), who was adopted and educated in Paris by Colonel Smyth\u201d, but no evidence of the existence of Maria Julia Dalziel has yet come to light.<ref name=AJC/>\n\nStuart recalled being orphaned by the death of his mother when he was two and his father when he was five, his father being drowned in a river, after falling off a bridge during an attempt to arrest him.<ref name=monthly/> According to Stuart, he was \u201cbred to Physic and was at one of the Scotch Universities\u201d and migrated from London to Virginia in 1763.<ref name=AJC/> An obituary  said that Stuart had been a Doctor of Medicine and had been educated \u201camid the Grampian hills\u201d, before attending the lectures of [[John Gregory (moralist)|Dr Gregory]] at Aberdeen,<ref name=monthly/> but no university career has been traced.<ref name=AJC/>\n\n==Life in America==\nStuart emigrated to the [[Thirteen Colonies]] and settled near [[Williamsburg, Virginia|Williamsburg]] in the [[Colony of Virginia]], where he later practised as a physician. By the 1770s, he had became a planter, renting plantations rather than owning them.<ref name=AJC/> The [[American Revolutionary War]] broke out, and on 15 October 1775, as a loyalist to Great Britain, Smyth quitted Virginia and joined the [[Loyalists fighting in the American Revolution|Loyalist forces]]. He served in several regiments in the rank of captain. He later wrote that at one time he commanded an armed sloop in [[Chesapeake Bay]] and at another raised a company of men for frontier work. More than once he was taken prisoner, and was shackled for eighteen months.<ref name=dnb/>\n\nAt New York, at about the end of 1777, Captain Smyth wrote his ''Narrative or Journal of Capt. John Ferdinand Dalziel Smyth, of the Queen's Rangers'', setting out his adventures, and was critical of the \u201cdeluded and mistaken\u201d rebels. This was printed in 1778.<ref>''Narrative or Journal of Capt. John Ferdinand Dalziel Smyth, of the Queen's Rangers'', reprinted in ''The Pennsylvania Magazine of History and Biography'', Vol. 39, No. 2 (1915), pp. 143-169</ref> He was then an officer of the [[Queen's Rangers]], a Loyalist regiment stationed at King's Bridge, New York, from July 1778.<ref name=AJC/> On 23 October 1778, he married Abigail Haugewout, the daughter of a loyalist farmer in Hempstead, on [[Long Island]], and their daughter Elizabeth was born in 1780.<ref name=hofstra/>\n\nStuart had leave to be absent from [[Muster (military)|musters]] in August and October 1778, but he was on duty in February 1779. In May 1779 he brought proceedings on various grounds against his commanding officer, Lieutenant-Colonel [[John Graves Simcoe]], but they were found to be \u201cMalicious, Frivolous, Vexatious, & Groundless\u201d. Simcoe claimed that Captain Smyth \u201cavoided military service whenever possible\u201d. He was sick in quarters at a muster on 24 June 1779, and not far into 1780, he returned to England, on the grounds of ill health.<ref name=AJC/>\n\n==England and West Indies==\nStuart remained an officer on half-pay for the duration of the American War. Commissioners had been appointed to assist loyalists who had suffered losses by the war, and in 1780 they awarded Stuart a temporary allowance of \u00a3100 a year, increasing this to \u00a3200 in 1781 and to \u00a3300 in 1783. He made an application to the Privy Council to be granted [[Long Island, Bahamas|Long Island]] in [[the Bahamas]], in view of his claimed losses of 3,300 acres in Virginia and Maryland, but he was not believed and this was rejected. His half-pay came to an end in 1783.<ref name=AJC/>\n\nIn 1784, allegations were made against Stuart to the claims commissioners, and his allowance was suspended. Stuart then wrote his book ''A Tour in the United States of America'',<ref name=dnb/> which was published by [[George Robinson (1737\u20131801)|George Robinson]] in 1784, agreeing to pay \u00a3160 for the printing. This, however, brought his account of himself to a wide public, and people who had known him in North America challenged it.<ref name=AJC/> \n\nIn 1785, Stuart went out to Jamaica, where he was appointed a Major \u201cin that Island only\u201d, but only remained there for sixteen days, as the result of a [[hurricane]].<ref name=AJC/>\n\nIn 1793, he adopted the name of Stuart, to mark his claim to descent from the [[House of Stuart]], and went on arguing his case to the government, without success.<ref name=dnb/>\n\nIn 1795, Stuart accepted a post as assistant barrack-master-general in [[San Domingo]] and to get there joined [[Admiral (Royal Navy)|Admiral]] [[Hugh Cloberry Christian|Sir Hugh Cloberry Christian]] on an expedition to the [[West Indies]]. He was shipwrecked three times in 1795 and 1796 and was present at the British capture of [[Saint Lucia]] and [[Martinique]]. In San Domingo, although not employed as a medical officer, he prescribed five grains of tartarised antimony and a tablespoonful of soft sugar for the treatment of [[yellow fever]], later claiming that this had proved a good treatment.<ref name=monthly/> On his return to England, Stuart continued to pursue his financial claims unsuccessfully, but continued to write in support of them.<ref name=dnb/>\n\nIn 1803, while Stuart was barrack-master at [[Billericay]], he suffered a severe beating which knocked out several of his teeth. In the final years of his life, he was barrack-master at [[Landguard Fort]], near [[Felixstowe]] in Suffolk. In 1814, Stuart retired from this work and settled in Vernon Place, [[Bloomsbury Square]].<ref name=monthly/>\n\n==Marriages and death==\nOn 23 October 1778, while he was Captain Smyth of the [[Queen's Rangers]], against her father\u2019s wishes Stuart married Abigail Haugewout, the 23-year-old daughter of Leffert Haugewout, a loyalist farmer of [[Hempstead (village), New York|Hempstead, New York]]. They set up house in [[Oyster Bay (town), New York|Oyster Bay]] and had one daughter, Elizabeth, born in October 1780, but by then Smyth had gone to live in England. His pregnant wife did not go with him and lived on until 1828, on a farm of fifteen acres in Hempstead which her father gave her. In 1797, Stuart returned on a visit and met his wife in New York. In 1802, his daughter Elizabeth married Gideon Nichols, a Hempstead merchant.<ref name=hofstra>[https://www.hofstra.edu/pdf/library/libspc_lisi_hart_nichols_fa.pdf Hart Nichols Collection, 1730-1930] at hofstra.edu (Special Collections Department, Long Island Studies Institute), pp. 4, 5, 10, 32: \u201dUpon her father\u2019s return to America seventeen years later, a relationship developed with him and his children from his second wife Eunice Grey (c1776-1818). This union created seven half brothers and sisters. They were Henry Stuart Smyth Stuart (1793-1794), Henrietta Maria Stuart Smyth Stuart (1797-1813), Mary Clementina Stuart Smyth Stuart (c1799-1826), Charles Henry Stuart Smyth Stuart (1802-1802), Constantine Wentworth Stuart Smyth Stuart (1805-1849), Spencer Percival Stuart Smyth Stuart (1807-c1807), and Ferdinand Stuart Smyth Stuart (c1812-1835).\u201d</ref>\n\nBefore his return to New York in 1797, Stuart had begun a second family in England with Eunice Gray, a girl of about sixteen. \nTheir son Henry was born in 1793, their first daughter, Henrietta Maria, in 1797,<ref>[https://www.ancestry.co.uk/interactive/1624/31280_199044-00310 Stuart \u2014 Henrietta Maria daughter of John Ferdinand Dalziel and Eunice] at ancestry.co.uk, accessed 21 April 2020 {{subscription}}</ref> and another daughter, Mary Clementina, about 1799, then another son, Charles Henry, in 1802.<ref name=hofstra/> On 7 September 1803, Stuart married Eunice Gray, at [[St Martin-in-the-Fields]], Westminster.<ref>\u201cJohn Ferdinand Dalziel Smyth Stuart and Eunice Gray, Marriage07/09/1803 Saint Martin in the  Fields, Westminster, London\u201c at ancestry.co.uk, accessed 21 April 2020 {{subscription}}</ref> Their third son, Constantine Wentworth, was born in August 1805,<ref>[https://www.ancestry.co.uk/interactive/1624/31280_199042-00424 \u201cConstantine Wentworth Stuart\u201d] baptism at ancestry.co.uk, accessed 21 April 2020, gives a date of birth, 11 August 1805, as well as a date of baptism, 9 September 1805 {{subscription}}</ref> a fourth, Spencer Percival, in 1807,<ref>[https://www.ancestry.co.uk/interactive/1624/31280_199042-00432 Spencer Percival Stuart. Son of Ferdinand and Eunice Smyth Stuart] baptism at ancestry.co.uk, accessed 21 April 2020, gives a date of birth, 14 June 1805, as well as a date of baptism, 14 July 1807 {{subscription}}</ref> and a fifth and last son, Ferdinand, in 1812. As a result of Stuart\u2019s visit to New York in 1797, his daughter Elizabeth at Hempstead was in contact with her new relations in England. Four of the children in England died young: Henry in 1794, Charles Henry in 1802, Spencer Percival about 1807, and Henrietta Maria in 1813,<ref name=hofstra/> just after her 16th birthday.<ref name=monthly/>\n\nOn 20 December 1814, Stuart was run over and killed by a carriage which hit him at the corner of [[Southampton Street, London|Southampton Street]], central London, leaving his second family destitute.<ref>[[Notes and Queries]], 2nd series, VIII, p. 495, IX, pp. 232, 334</ref> He was buried on 1 January 1815 at [[Marylebone]], where the parish register notes that he was of St George\u2019s parish, [[Bloomsbury]].<ref>''Burials in the Parish of St Mary-le-Bone'',  [https://www.ancestry.co.uk/interactive/1559/31280_194703-00275 p. 2] at ancestry.co.uk, accessed 21 April 2020 {{subscription}}</ref> A six-page obituary in the [[Monthly Magazine]] celebrated Stuart\u2019s life and appealed on behalf of his dependants \n{{Quote|\u201cIt may be hoped that some friend of the royal house of Guelph will do Humanity the justice to  point out to them the necessities of this withered branch of the once-royal house of Stuart.\u201d<ref name=monthly/>}}\n\nIn January 1815, [[Lord Palmerston]], Secretary for War, agreed to Eunice Stuart being paid \u00a325 a year from the Compassionate Fund, including \u00a315 for the support of her children. In June 1816, the [[George IV of the United Kingdom|Prince Regent]], the future George IV, granted Eunice a pension of \u00a350 a year from the [[Civil List]], to supplement the grant from the Compassionate Fund, which she reported to Palmerston. She died in 1818, and Palmerston increased the money paid for the children to \u00a324 a year. A neighbour paid Constantine Wentworth\u2019s education at [[Charterhouse School]], [[Smithfield, London|Smithfield]].<ref name=AJC/>\n\nTwo of Stuart\u2019s remaining children died in their twenties, Mary Clementina in 1826, and Ferdinand in 1835. Constantine Wentworth lived until 1849, and married. In July 1828, he was an officer in the [[6th Regiment of Foot]] and was promoted from Ensign to Lieutenant without purchase.<ref>\u201cEnsign Constantine Wentworth Stuart Smyth Stuart\u201d in ''[[The London Gazette]]'', Issue 18495, 12 August 1828, p. 1534, col. 1</ref> He resigned his commission at Poona, in 1832, and later visited his half-sister, Elizabeth, in Hempstead, New York.<ref name=AJC/> She had a number of children and grandchildren, lived until 1858, and left many descendants.<ref name=hofstra/>\n\n==Published works==\n*John Ferdinand Dalziel Smyth, ''Narrative or Journal of Capt. John Ferdinand Dalziel Smyth, of the Queen's Rangers'' (New York, 1778), is Stuart\u2019s first known substantial publication.<ref name=AJC/> \n*John Ferdinand Dalziel Smyth, ''A Tour in the United States of America'' (London, G. Robinson, 1784), a much longer work, describes Stuart\u2019s recent travels there and his activities during the War of Independence.<ref name=dnb/> The book was republished in 2010 in a 468-page paperback by [[Kessinger Publishing]] of [[Whitefish, Montana]], {{ISBN|978-1162797267}}. It was translated into French and in 1791 published by Buisson of Paris under the title ''Voyage dans les \u00c9tats-Unis de l'Am\u00e9rique, fait en 1784''.<ref> [https://openlibrary.org/books/OL25938880M/Voyage_dans_les_\u00c9tats-Unis_de_l'Am\u00e9rique_fait_en_1784 ''Voyage dans les \u00c9tats-Unis de l'Am\u00e9rique, fait en 1784'' at openlibrary.org</ref> Stuart\u2019s view of the country has been called \n{{Quote|\u201c...vigorous but not flattering. The republican opinions of the colonists were obnoxious to a loyalist, while their barbarous manners were repellent to a gentleman.\u201d<ref name=dnb/>}}\n* John Ferdinand Smyth Stuart, ''A Letter to Lord Henry Petty on Coercive Vaccination'' (London, 1807) is a forceful medical and political argument against [[vaccination]] addressed to [[Henry Petty-Fitzmaurice, 3rd Marquess of Lansdowne|Lord Henry Petty]], the youthful [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]].<ref>Chambers, Book of Days, vol. I, p. 628</ref> It was motivated by the death of one of his own children.<ref name=AJC/>\n*Ferdinand Smyth Stuart, ''The Case of Ferdinand Smyth Stuart'' (London, 1807) returned to Stuart\u2019s complaints about his treatment by the British government.<ref name=dnb/>\n*Ferdinand Smyth Stuart, ''Destiny and Fortitude: An Historical Poem: In Sixteen Elegies: Being a Detail of the Misfortunes of the Illustrious House of Stuart'' (London, 1808), followed shortly after the death of [[Henry Benedict Stuart]], the last legitimate Stuart descendant of [[James II of England|King James II]], and celebrated his own family\u2019s [[Jacobitism]].<ref name=dnb/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n==External links==\n*[https://www.worldcat.org/identities/lccn-n85247830/ Stuart, John Ferdinand Smyth 1745\u20131814] at [[WorldCat]]\n*[https://www.jstor.org/stable/20086210 ''Narrative or Journal of Capt. John Ferdinand Dalziel Smyth, of the Queen's Rangers'' (1778)], reprinted in ''The Pennsylvania Magazine of History and Biography'', Vol. 39, No. 2 (1915), in open [[JSTOR]] collections\n*[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6m76vtrNAJkC&pg=PA36 \u201cMemoirs of FERDINAND SMYTH STUART, M.D., Major in the British Army, and Grandson of the Duke of Monmouth\u201d], obituary in ''The Monthly Magazine'', 1 February 1815, pp. 36\u201341 \n*[http://anthonyjcamp.com/page20.htm John Ferdinand Smyth: loyalist and liar], by [[Anthony J. Camp]], at anthonyjcamp.com, as published in ''Genealogists' Magazine'', vol. 31, no. 11 (September 2015)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stuart, John Ferdinand Smyth}}\n[[Category:1745 births]]\n[[Category:1814 deaths]]\n[[Category:18th-century Scottish medical doctors]]\n[[Category:Loyalist military personnel of the American Revolutionary War]]\n[[Category:House of Stuart]]\n", "name_user": "Moonraker", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMarriages and death", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Ferdinand_Smyth_Stuart"}
{"title_page": "1932 Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox college sports team season\n| mode = football\n| year = 1932\n| team = Western Kentucky Hilltoppers\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| conference = Southern Intercollegiate Athletic Association\n| short_conf = SIAA\n| record = 8\u20131\n| conf_record = 6\u20130\n| head_coach = [[Ernest R. Miller]]\n| hc_year = 1st\n| off_scheme =  \n| def_scheme = \n| stadium = \n| champion = SIAA champion\n}}\nThe '''1932 Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football team''' represented [[Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football|Western Kentucky State College]] in the [[1932 college football season]].  They were coached by [[Ernest R. Miller]] and won the [[Southern Intercollegiate Athletic Association|SIAA]] championship.  Fletcher Holeman was the team captain.<ref>[https://wkusports.com/documents/2019/7/17/2019_WKU_Football_Media_Guide.pdf WKU Football Media Guide retrieved 31 March 2020]</ref>\n\n==Schedule==\n\nSeptember 24, ''Evansville''  '''Won''' 38-0 <br>\nOctober 1. Transylvania  '''Won''' 27-7 <br>\nOctober 8, at ''Vanderbilt''  '''Lost''' 0-26 <br>\nOctober 15, at Middle Tennessee  '''Won''' 21-7 <br>\nOctober 22, at Murray State  '''Won''' 6-0 <br>\nNovember 5, Georgetown (Ky.) <small>(Homecoming)</small>  '''Won''' 24-0 <br>\nNovember 12, Union (Tenn.)  '''Won''' 46-0 <br>\nNovember 19, ''Eastern Kentucky''  '''Won''' 1-0 <small>Forfeit</small><br>\nNovember 19, Louisville  '''Won''' 58-0 <br>\n''Italic'' non-conference game\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football navbox}}\n{{SIAA football champions}}\n\n[[Category:1932 Southern Intercollegiate Athletic Association football season|Western Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football seasons]]\n[[Category:1932 in Kentucky|Western Kentucky Football]]\n\n{{collegefootball-1930s-season-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n| mode = football\n| year = 1932\n| team = Western Kentucky Hilltoppers\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| conference = Southern Intercollegiate Athletic Association\n| short_conf = SIAA\n| record = 8\u20131\n| conf_record = 6\u20130\n| head_coach = [[Ernest R. Miller]]\n| hc_year = 1st\n| off_scheme =  \n| def_scheme = \n| stadium = \n| champion = SIAA champion\n}}\nThe '''1932 Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football team''' represented [[Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football|Western Kentucky State College]] in the [[1932 college football season]].  They were coached by [[Ernest R. Miller]] and won the [[Southern Intercollegiate Athletic Association|SIAA]] championship.  Fletcher Holeman was the team captain.<ref>[https://wkusports.com/documents/2019/7/17/2019_WKU_Football_Media_Guide.pdf WKU Football Media Guide retrieved 31 March 2020]</ref>\n\n==Schedule==\n\nSeptember 24, ''Evansville''  '''Won''' 38-0 <br>\nOctober 1. Transylvania  '''Won''' 27-7 <br>\nOctober 8, at ''Vanderbilt''  '''Lost''' 0-26 <br>\nOctober 15, at Middle Tennessee  '''Won''' 21-7 <br>\nOctober 22, at Murray State  '''Won''' 6-0 <br>\nNovember 5, Georgetown (Ky.) <small>(Homecoming)</small>  '''Won''' 24-0 <br>\nNovember 12, Union (Tenn.)  '''Won''' 46-0 <br>\nNovember 19, ''Eastern Kentucky''  '''Won''' 1-0 <small>Forfeit</small><br>\nNovember 19, Louisville  '''Won''' 58-0 <br>\n''Italic'' non-conference game\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football navbox}}\n{{SIAA football champions}}\n\n[[Category:1932 Southern Intercollegiate Athletic Association football season|Western Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football seasons]]\n[[Category:1932 in Kentucky|Western Kentucky Football]]\n\n{{collegefootball-1930s-season-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jweiss11", "label": "safe", "comment": "cleanup infobox", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1932_Western_Kentucky_Hilltoppers_football_team"}
{"title_page": "RAF Leeming", "text_new": "{{Short description|Royal Air Force base in Yorkshire, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox military installation\n| name = RAF Leeming\n| ensign=Ensign of the Royal Air Force.svg\n| ensign_size=90px\n| native_name = \n| partof = \n| location = \n| nearest_town = [[Leeming, North Yorkshire|Leeming]], [[North Yorkshire]]\n| country = England\n| image =File:Hawk - RIAT 2007 (2374490391).jpg \n| caption =A BAE Hawk of No. 100 Squadron \n| image2 = Leeming.gif\n| image2_size = 100px\n| caption2 = ''Straight and True''<ref>{{cite book|last1=Pine|first1=L.G.|title=A dictionary of mottoes|date=1983|publisher=Routledge & Kegan Paul|location=London|isbn=0-7100-9339-X|page=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofmott00tion/page/222 222]|edition=1|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofmott00tion/page/222}}</ref>\n| pushpin_map = North Yorkshire\n| pushpin_label = RAF Leeming\n| pushpin_map_caption = Shown within North Yorkshire\n| coordinates = {{Coord|54|17|33|N|001|32|08|W|region:GB_type:airport|display=inline,title}}\n| type = Support station\n| code = \n| site_area = {{convert|508|ha|acres}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/defence-estates-development-plan-dedp-2009|title=Defence Estates Development Plan 2009 \u2013 Annex A|date=3 July 2009|website=GOV.UK|publisher=Ministry of Defence|page=12|accessdate=27 March 2019}}</ref>\n| height = \n| ownership = [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]]\n| operator = [[Royal Air Force]]\n| controlledby = [[No. 1 Group RAF|No. 1 Group (Air Combat)]]\n| open_to_public = \n| condition = Operational\n| built = {{Start date|1939}}\n| builder = \n| used = 1940 \u2013 present<!--{{End date|1946}} -->\n| materials = \n| fate = \n| battles = \n| events = \n| current_commander = [[Group Captain]] Blythe Crawford\n| past_commanders = <!-- past notable commander(s) -->\n| garrison = \n| occupants = \n* [[No. 100 Squadron RAF|No. 100 Squadron]]\n* [[Joint Forward Air Controller Training and Standards Unit]]\n* [[No. 90 Signals Unit RAF|No. 90 Signals Unit]]\n* [[No. 34 Squadron RAF Regiment]]\n* [[No. 607 Squadron RAF|No. 607 Squadron (RAuxAF)]]\n* [[No. 609 Squadron RAF|No. 609 Squadron (RAuxAF Regiment)]]\n* [[Northumbrian Universities Air Squadron]]\n* [[No. 11 Air Experience Flight RAF|No. 11 Air Experience Flight]]\n* Mountain Rescue Team\n''See [[#Based units|Based units]] section for full list.''\n| elevation = {{Convert|40.5|m|0}}\n| IATA = QXL\n| ICAO = EGXE\n| FAA = \n| TC = \n| LID = \n| GPS = \n| WMO = 03257\n| r1-number = 16/34\n| r1-length = {{Convert|2291|m|0}}\n| r1-surface = [[Asphalt]]\n| website = {{URL|http://www.raf.mod.uk/rafleeming/}}\n| footnotes ='''Source''': UK MIL AIP Leeming<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aidu.mod.uk/aip/pdf/ad/EGXE-Leeming-Combined.pdf|title=UK MIL AIP Leeming|date=28 February 2019|website=UK Military AIP|publisher=No.1 Aeronautical Information Documents Unit|accessdate=27 March 2019}}</ref>}}\n\n'''Royal Air Force Leeming''' or '''RAF Leeming''' is a [[Royal Air Force]] station located near [[Leeming, North Yorkshire|Leeming]], [[North Yorkshire]], [[England]]. It was opened in 1940 and was jointly used by the RAF and the [[Royal Canadian Air Force]] (RCAF). Between 1950 and 1991, it operated mostly as a training base with [[Quick Reaction Force]] (QRF) [[Tornado F3]] fighters based there in the latter stages of the Cold War and into the early 21st century. Since 2006, it has become the home of the deployable RAF communications cadre ([[90 Signals Unit]]) and the home of No. 135 [[Expeditionary Air Wing]].\n\n==History==\n===1930s===\nThe area at the extreme western edge of the base was used in the 1930s by local flying enthusiasts. It took the name of ''Londonderry Aerodrome'' as it was closest to the hamlet of [[Londonderry, North Yorkshire|Londonderry]] in North Yorkshire.{{sfn|Coupland|1997|p=xviii}}<ref>{{cite journal |title=Air Day Aerodromes|journal=Flight Magazine |date=24 May 1934 |volume=26 |issue=1,326 |page=508 |publisher=Royal Aero Club |location=London |issn=0015-3710}}</ref> In the late 1930s, the Royal Air Force bought up the aerodrome and most of the surrounding land to convert it into an RAF airfield, which became known as Royal Air Force Leeming. Part of the buildup of the base included building a decoy airfield at [[Burneston]], some {{convert|4|mi}} to the south.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Halpenny |first1=Bruce Barrymore |title=Action stations 4; Military Airfields of Yorkshire |date=1982 |publisher=Patrick Stephens |location=Cambridge |isbn=0-85059-532-0 |page=107 |edition=2}}</ref>\n\n===1940s===\n[[File:Royal Air Force 1939-1945- Bomber Command CH3139.jpg|thumb|This Stirling, N3641/MG-D, seen being prepared for a flight, was the second Stirling to be delivered to No. 7 Squadron at Leeming and took part in their first raid over [[Rotterdam]] on the night of 10\u201311 February 1941.]]\nThe station opened in 1940 as a bomber station during the [[Second World War]]. In 1943 the station was assigned to [[No. 6 Group RCAF|No. 6 Group]] [[Royal Canadian Air Force]] (RCAF) with a sub-station at [[RAF Skipton-on-Swale]]. The main aircraft operated were [[Handley Page Halifax|Halifax]] [[bomber]]s.<ref>{{Harvnb|Halley|1988|pp=494\u2013510.}}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Delve|1994|p=62.}}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Sturtivant and Hamlin|2007|pp=97, 125\u2013126.}}</ref>\n\nA detachment of [[No. 219 Squadron RAF]] used the airfield between 4 October 1939 and 12 October 1940 when the main section of the squadron was at [[RAF Catterick]] flying the [[Bristol Blenheim]] IF.<ref name=\"Jefford1988p72\">{{Harvnb|Jefford|1988|p=72.}}</ref>\n*[[No. 10 Squadron RAF]] between 8 July 1940 and 5 July 1942 flying the [[Handley Page Halifax]] Mks I & II.<ref name=\"Jefford1988p27\">{{Harvnb|Jefford|1988|p=27.}}</ref>\n*[[No. 7 Squadron RAF]] reformed at the airfield on 1 August 1940 with the [[Short Stirling]] I before moving to [[RAF Oakington]] on 29 October 1940.<ref name=\"Jefford1988p26\">{{Harvnb|Jefford|1988|p=26.}}</ref>\n*[[No. 102 Squadron RAF]] between 25 August 1940 and 1 September 1940 flying the [[Armstrong Whitworth Whitley]] V before moving to [[RAF Prestwick]].<ref name=\"Jefford1988p54\">{{Harvnb|Jefford|1988|p=54.}}</ref>\n*[[No. XXXV Squadron RAF|No. 35 Squadron RAF]] between 20 November 1940 and 5 December 1940 using the Halifax I before moving to [[RAF Linton-on-Ouse]].<ref name=\"Jefford1988p37\">{{Harvnb|Jefford|1988|p=37.}}</ref>\n*[[No. 77 Squadron RAF]] between 5 September 1941 and 6 May 1942 flying the Whitley V before moving to [[RAF Chivenor]].<ref name=\"Jefford1988p48\">{{Harvnb|Jefford|1988|p=48.}}</ref>\n*[[No. 408 Squadron RCAF]] between 14 September 1942 and 27 August 1943 with the Halifax V and I before moving to [[RAF Linton-on-Ouse]].<ref name=\"Jefford1988p90\">{{Harvnb|Jefford|1988|p=90.}}</ref>\n*1659 HCU RAF 1941\u20131942\n*[[No. 424 Squadron RCAF]] between 8 April 1943 and 3 May 1943 using the [[Vickers Wellington]] X before moving to [[RAF Dalton]].<ref name=\"Jefford1988p91\">{{Harvnb|Jefford|1988|p=91.}}</ref>\n*[[No. 427 Squadron RCAF]] between 5 May 1943 and 31 May 1946 when the squadron disbanded. The squadron initially used the Halifax V and III before switching to the [[Avro Lancaster]] Mk.I and III in March 1945.<ref name=\"Jefford1988p91\"/>\n*[[No. 429 Squadron RCAF]] between 13 August 1943 and 31 May 1946 when the squadron disbanded. The squadron initially used the Halifax V and III before switching to the [[Avro Lancaster]] Mk.I and III in March 1945.<ref name=\"Jefford1988p91\"/>\n\n===1950\u20131990===\n\nFollowing the war, the station became a night-fighter base, equipped initially with [[de Havilland Mosquito|Mosquito]] and then [[Gloster Meteor|Meteor]] and [[Gloster Javelin|Javelin]] aircraft before becoming a [[RAF Training Command|Training Command]] airfield in 1961. The station was then home to ''No. 3 Flying Training School'', equipped with the [[BAC Jet Provost|Jet Provost]] aircraft.<ref>[http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/AboutDefence/WhatWeDo/HealthandSafety/DSC/NoiseInsulationGrantScheme/DscOhsNigsRafLeeming.htm History of Airfield] from RAF Leeming Noise Insulation Grant Scheme survey report</ref>\n\nThere were also several other units using the airfield during the same period, these were:\n*[[No. 228 Operational Conversion Unit RAF|228 Operational Conversion Unit]] RAF 1948\u20131961<ref>{{Harvnb|Delve|2006|p=169}}</ref>\n*[[No. 3 Flying Training School RAF]] 1961\u20131984<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205072534/http://www.raf.mod.uk/rafwittering/aboutus/3fts.cfm|title=No 3 Flight Training School and No. 6 Flying Training School|publisher=Ministry of Defence|accessdate=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Northumbrian Universities Air Squadron]] 1974\u2013Present<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080607060111/http://www.raf.mod.uk/rafleeming/aboutus/nuas.cfm|title=RAF \u2013 Northumbrian Universities Air Squadron|website=www.raf.mod.uk|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref>\n*[[No. 11 Air Experience Flight RAF|No. 11 Air Experience Flight]] 1980\u2013Present<ref>{{cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/764794/12054.pdf|title=Information regarding air cadets and RAF air experience flights|date=8 October 2018|publisher=Ministry of Defence|accessdate=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn January 1987, the airfield closed for one year to allow installation of [[Hardened Aircraft Shelters]] (HAS). RAF Leeming became the home base for three Tornado squadrons over the next twenty years.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Delve|first1=Ken|title=Northern England : Co. Durham, Cumbria, Isle of Man, Lancashire, Merseyside, Manchester, Northumberland, Tyne & Wear, Yorkshire|date=2006|publisher=Crowood|location=Ramsbury|isbn=1-86126-809-2|page=170}}</ref>\n\n===1990\u2013present===\n\nLeeming functioned as a training base until 1988 when it became a front line base in the air defence role equipped with [[Panavia Tornado|Tornado]] [[RAF Tornado F3|F3]]s. Initially it hosted Nos [[No. 11 Squadron RAF|11(F)]], [[No. 23 Squadron RAF|23]], and [[No. XXV Squadron RAF|25(F)]] Squadrons, all flying the F3. 23 Squadron was disbanded on 1 March 1994 and its air and ground crews dispersed across the Station's remaining two squadrons.{{sfn|Jefford|2001|p=35}} This left two Tornado squadrons, which were half of the air defence fighter squadrons of the RAF. 11 Squadron was disbanded in October 2005. The last Tornado squadron at Leeming, No 25(F) Squadron, disbanded on 4 April 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.raf.mod.uk/news/articles/no-25-squadron-returning-to-fly-the-hawk-t2/|title=No. 25 Squadron returning to fly the Hawk T2|publisher=Ministry of Defence|accessdate=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe station's air traffic control unit was named the best in the Royal Air Force in February 2012, winning the Raytheon Falconer Trophy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/PeopleInDefence/LeemingsAirTrafficControlSquadronNamedBestInRaf.htm |title=Leeming's Air Traffic Control Squadron named best in RAF |date=27 February 2012 |publisher=Ministry of Defence |accessdate=3 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 April 2020, the government announced that [[alpha testing]] of a prototype of the government's [[COVID-19 app]] was in progress at RAF Leeming.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kelion|first=Leo|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-52381103|title=NHS coronavirus-tracing app is tested at RAF base|date=22 April 2020|work=BBC News|accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Role and operations==\n===Air combat training===\nThe only remaining jets are the [[BAE Systems Hawk|BAe Hawk]]s of [[No. 100 Squadron RAF|100 Squadron]] which arrived in 1995 and provide an air combat training service as well as support to the [[Joint Forward Air Controller Training and Standards Unit]] (JFACTSU).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023061244/https://www.raf.mod.uk/rafleeming/aboutus/jfactsuhome.cfm|title=JFACTSU Home|publisher=Ministry of Defence|accessdate=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Expeditionary Air Wing===\nNo. 135 Expeditionary Air Wing (No. 135 EAW) was formed at Leeming on 1 April 2006 to create a deployable air force structure.<ref>{{Harvnb|Cotter|2008|p=33.}}</ref>\n\n===Supported units===\n607 (County of Durham) Squadron reformed at RAF Leeming on 5 January 2015. The Squadron formerly flew fighter aircraft and was disbanded in 1957. The squadron is a General Service Support (GSS) unit with many diverse roles such as chef, driver, intelligence analyst and suppliers.<ref>{{cite web|title=RAF 607 County of Durham|url=http://www.raf.mod.uk/organisation/reserves/607-Country-of-Durham.cfm|website=raf.mod.uk|accessdate=23 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Based units==\nFlying and notable non-flying units based at RAF Leeming.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.raf.mod.uk/our-organisation/stations/raf-leeming/|title=RAF Leeming \u2013 Who's Based Here?|website=Royal Air Force|accessdate=14 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Royal Air Force ===\n'''[[No. 1 Group RAF|No. 1 Group (Air Combat) RAF]]'''\n*[[No. 100 Squadron RAF|No. 100 Squadron]]  \u2013 [[BAE Systems Hawk|Hawk T1A]]\n*[[Joint Forward Air Controller Training and Standards Unit|Joint Forward Air Control Training and Standardisation Unit (JFACTSU)]]\n*[[No. 607 Squadron RAF|No. 607 (County of Durham) Squadron (Royal Auxiliary Air Force)]]\n\n'''[[No. 2 Group RAF|No. 2 Group (Air Combat Support) RAF]]'''\n* [[RAF Force Protection Force Headquarters|No. 2 RAF Force Protection Wing]]\n** No. 2 Force Protection Wing Headquarters\n**[[No. 34 Squadron RAF Regiment]]\n**[[No. 609 Squadron RAF|No. 609 (West Riding) Squadron (Royal Auxiliary Air Force) Regiment]]\n\n'''[[No. 22 Group RAF|No. 22 Group (Training) RAF]]'''\n* [[No. 11 Air Experience Flight RAF|No. 11 Air Experience Flight]] \u2013 [[Grob G 115|Tutor T1]]\n* [[Northumbrian Universities Air Squadron]] \u2013 Tutor T1\n*Operational Training Centre<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gleeson |first1=Janet |title=New Station Officer for RAF Leeming |url=https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/17366679.new-commander-at-north-yorkshire-raf-base/ |accessdate=5 October 2019 |work=The Northern Echo |date=20 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''[[No. 38 Group RAF|No. 38 Group (Air Combat Service Support) RAF]]'''\n* [[No. 90 Signals Unit RAF|No. 90 Signals Unit]] \n** Operational Information Services Wing\n*** No. 1 (Engineering Support) Squadron\n*** No. 5 (Information Services) Squadron\n*** Capability and Innovation Squadron\n*** Operations Squadron\n** [[Tactical Communications Wing RAF|Tactical Communications Wing]]\n***No. 2 Field Communications Squadron\n***No. 3 Field Communications Squadron\n***No. 4 Field Communications Squadron\n* [[Royal Air Force Mountain Rescue Service|RAF Leeming Mountain Rescue Team (MRT)]]\n\nThe deployable elements of the station structure form the core of an [[Expeditionary Air Wing]], [[No. 135 Expeditionary Air Wing RAF|No. 135 Expeditionary Air Wing]]. For Exercise 'Griffin Strike 2016' in April 2016, No. 135 EAW became the combined French-British No. 135 Combined Expeditionary Air Wing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.raf.mod.uk/news/archive/raf-and-french-air-force-celebrate-strategic-alliance-21042016|title=Royal Air Force \u2013 News by Date|website=www.raf.mod.uk|accessdate=1 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Reduce to Produce===\nRAF Leeming has been host to a reverse assembly line process (Reduce to Produce (RTP)) whereby redundant Tornado aircraft are brought into one of the hangars at RAF Leeming and stripped of all usable components. The process started with the F3 variant of the aircraft as it was the first to be withdrawn completely from service, and moved onto the GR4 variant later. In October 2017, it was announced that the full retirement of the Tornado aircraft from RAF service in 2019 meant that this process will end with the loss of 245 British Aerospace jobs between RAF Leeming and [[RAF Marham]]. [[BAE Systems]] are undertaking the RTP process.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nearly 2,000 jobs at risk as BAE Systems adjusts to declining workload The Engineer|url=https://www.theengineer.co.uk/nearly-2000-jobs-at-risk-as-bae-systems-adjusts-to-declining-workload/|website=www.theengineer.co.uk|accessdate=22 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=RAF Leeming RTP \u00ab News \u00ab Fast Air Photography|url=http://www.fast-air.co.uk/raf-leeming-rtp/|website=www.fast-air.co.uk|accessdate=22 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Flanagan|first1=Emily|title=Jobs lost as BAE plans shake-up|work=Darlington and Stockton Times|issue=41-2017|date=13 October 2017|page=5|issn=2040-3933}}</ref>\n\n==Future==\nIn March 2019, the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] indicated that RAF Leeming, alongside [[RAF Waddington]] and [[RAF Wittering]], was being considered as the future home of the [[Red Arrows|RAF Aerobatic Team]] the Red Arrows. The team are expected to relocate from their existing base at [[RAF Scampton]] when it closes in 2022.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-47617062|title=Three choices for new Red Arrows base|date=18 March 2019|work=BBC News|accessdate=19 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"yorkpost_arrows\">{{cite newspaper | title=Here's why this RAF base in Yorkshire could be the new home of the Red Arrows | date=25 July 2018 | author=Grace Newton | url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/here-s-why-this-raf-base-in-yorkshire-could-be-the-new-home-of-the-red-arrows-1-9269094 | newspaper=[[The Yorkshire Post]]|accessdate=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Accidents and incidents==\n\n* 21 February 1944 \u2013 a RCAF Halifax, LV836, of No. 427 Sqn crashed into farmland at [[Romanby]], creating a fireball and killing all seven crew on impact. The aircraft had left RAF Leeming nine minutes earlier, at 00:15, on a bombing mission to [[Stuttgart]]. On 10 March 2010 a memorial to the crew was unveiled at the crash site, which is now part of Romanby Golf & Country Club.<ref>{{cite web|title=Memorial tribute to Halifax bomber crew unveiled at RAF Leeming|url=http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/news/5046553.Memorial_tribute_to_Halifax_bomber_crew_unveiled/|website=www.yorkpress.co.uk|accessdate=25 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Leeming Memorial \u2013 Romanby Golf Course \u2013 Halifax LV836 |url=http://www.427squadron.com/news_file/leeming_memorial_pics.html |website=427 Squadron Association |accessdate=25 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Air Crew Fallen Remembered at Memorial Unveiling|url=https://www.raf.mod.uk/news/archive.cfm?storyid=472D8793-5056-A318-A80F23E1B15B0156|website=www.raf.mod.uk/|accessdate=25 August 2017}}</ref>\n* 13 August 1951 \u2013 two aircraft from RAF Leeming collided over [[Hudswell, North Yorkshire|Hudswell]], near to [[Richmond, North Yorkshire|Richmond]], [[North Yorkshire]]. A cadet in the [[No. 228 Operational Conversion Unit]] [[Vickers Wellington|Wellington]] aircraft was given the only serviceable parachute by Flight Lieutenant [[John Quinton]], shown how to operate it and ordered to bale out. The other eight crew members of both aircraft died when their aircraft hit the ground.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wellington PG367.|url=http://www.yorkshire-aircraft.co.uk/aircraft/planes/dales/pg367.html|website=www.yorkshire-aircraft.co.uk|accessdate=25 August 2017}}</ref>\n* 22 October 1999 \u2013 a 100 Sqn Hawk struck a bridge and crashed into an unoccupied building near the village of [[Shap]], killing the pilot and navigator. The RAF Board of Inquiry suggested that aircrew fatigue may have contributed to the accident. A jury returned a verdict of accidental death.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fatal RAF jet crash linked to 'excessive' workload of pilot|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/fatal-raf-jet-crash-linked-to-excessive-workload-of-pilot-129461.html|website=www.independent.co.uk|accessdate=26 August 2017}}</ref>\n* 28 January 2016 \u2013 during a training sortie, the pilot of a 100 Sqn Hawk experienced partial loss of vision.  The base commander considered instructing the pilot to eject over the [[North Sea]], but instead scrambled another Hawk, flown by an instructor. The two aircraft [[formation flying|flew in formation]] to Leeming, and conducted a successful [[talk down aircraft landing|talk down landing]].<ref>{{cite web|title='Blind' RAF pilot saved by wingman who talked him down|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/defence/12132567/Blind-RAF-pilot-saved-by-wingman-who-talked-him-down.html|website=www.telegraph.co.uk|accessdate=26 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Heritage==\n===Gate Guardian===\n[[File:Tornado F3 ZH552 gate guardian RAF Leeming.jpg|thumb|A Tornado F3 aircraft now stands as a gate guardian outside the main gate of RAF Leeming in North Yorkshire]]\nLeeming's [[gate guardian]] is now a [[Panavia Tornado|Tornado F3]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Foster|first1=Mark|title=Fighter jet on permanent sentry duty|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/13327364.Fighter_jet_on_permanent_sentry_duty/|accessdate=29 August 2017|work=The Northern Echo|date=11 June 2015}}</ref> commemorating its history as an air defence base, and the fact that many Tornados were scrapped/Reduced To Produce here.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.urbanghostsmedia.com/2013/09/reduced-to-produce-the-end-of-the-rafs-tornado-f3-interceptor-force/|title=Urban Ghosts Media is coming soon|website=Urban Ghosts Media is coming soon}}</ref> The previous gate guardian ''XA634'' is the world's only surviving [[Gloster Javelin]] FAW4, which spent most of its life as a testbed at the [[Gloster Aircraft Company]] and was offered for sale by tender in September 2014 by the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/355934/Sale-of-Gloster-Javelin-_FAW-4-_aircraft.pdf |title=SALE OF QTY 1 GLOSTER JAVELIN FAW 4 AIRCRAFT |date=1 September 2014 |publisher=Ministry of Defence |accessdate=20 January 2015}}</ref> In December 2014 it was announced that Gloucestershire Jet Age Museum had won the tender and purchased the aircraft.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-gloucestershire-30622904|title=BBC News \u2013 Gloucestershire Jet Age Museum buys Gloster Javelin|work=[[BBC Online]]|accessdate=20 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[List of Royal Air Force stations]]\n\n==References==\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Cotter |first1=Jarrod |title=Royal Air Force celebrating 90 years |year=2008 |publisher= Key Publishing Ltd |location= [[Stamford, Lincolnshire|Stamford]], UK|isbn=978-0-946219-11-7 |ref= {{harvid|Cotter|2008}} }}\n*{{cite book|last=Coupland|first=Peter|title=Straight and True: A History of Royal Air Force Leeming|location= London|publisher=Leo Cooper|year=1997|isbn=0-85052-569-1|ref={{Harvid|Coupland|1997}} }}\n*{{cite book|last=Delve|first=Ken|title=The Sourcebook of the RAF|location=Shrewsbury, Shropshire, UK|publisher=Airlife Publishing|year=1994|isbn=1-85310-451-5|ref={{Harvid|Delve|1994}} }}\n*{{cite book|last1=Delve|first1=Ken|title=Northern England : Co. Durham, Cumbria, Isle of Man, Lancashire, Merseyside, Manchester, Northumberland, Tyne & Wear, Yorkshire|date=2006|publisher=Crowood|location=Ramsbury|isbn=1-86126-809-2|ref={{Harvid|Delve|2006}} }}\n*{{cite book|last=Halley|first=James J.|title=The Squadrons of the Royal Air Force & Commonwealth, 1918-1988|location=Tonbridge, Kent, UK|publisher=Air-Britain (Historians) |year=1988|isbn=0-85130-164-9|ref={{Harvid|Halley|1988}} }}\n*{{cite book|last=Jefford|first= C.G.|title=RAF Squadrons, a Comprehensive Record of the Movement and Equipment of all RAF Squadrons and their Antecedents since 1912 (First edition)|l